title="Daniel Gratzer">Daniel Gratzer</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors><fr:meta
name="venue"><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-010U.xml"
addr="jms-010U"
title="CMU HoTT Seminar">CMU HoTT Seminar</fr:link></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>In 1997, <fr:link
type="local"
href="hofmann-streicher-1997.xml"
addr="hofmann-streicher-1997"
title="Lifting Grothendieck universes">Hofmann and Streicher</fr:link> introduced an explicit technique to lift a Grothendieck universe <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>𝓤</mml:mi></mml:math> from <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>𝐒𝐞𝐭</mml:mi></mml:math> into the category of <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>𝐒𝐞𝐭</mml:mi></mml:math>-valued presheaves on a <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>𝓤</mml:mi></mml:math>-small category <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>𝓑</mml:mi></mml:math>. More recently, <fr:link
type="local"
href="awodey-2022-universes.xml"
addr="awodey-2022-universes"
title="On Hofmann–Streicher universes">Awodey</fr:link> presented an elegant functorial analysis of this construction in terms of the <fr:em>‘categorical nerve’</fr:em>, the right adjoint to the functor that takes a presheaf to its category of elements; in particular, applying the categorical nerve to the universal <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>𝓤</mml:mi></mml:math>-small discrete fibration gives the generic family of <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>𝓤</mml:mi></mml:math>’s Hofmann–Streicher lifting.</fr:p><fr:p>Although <fr:link
type="local"
href="awodey-2022-universes.xml"
addr="awodey-2022-universes"
title="On Hofmann–Streicher universes">Awodey</fr:link> has investigated Hofmann–Streicher lifting in terms of a 1-functor <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>𝐂𝐚𝐭</mml:mi><mml:mo>→</mml:mo> <mml:mrow><mml:mi>𝐏𝐫</mml:mi>
  <mml:mrow>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[(]]></mml:mo>
   <mml:mi>𝓑</mml:mi>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[)]]></mml:mo>
  </mml:mrow>
 </mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math>, his analysis can be extended to a 2-functor <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>𝐂𝐚𝐭</mml:mi><mml:mo>→</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>𝐅𝐢𝐛</mml:mi>
  <mml:mrow>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[(]]></mml:mo>
   <mml:mi>𝓑</mml:mi>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[)]]></mml:mo>
  </mml:mrow>
 </mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math> that is observed by <fr:link
type="local"
href="weber-2007.xml"
addr="weber-2007"
title="Yoneda structures from 2-toposes">Weber</fr:link> to be right 2-adjoint to the 2-functor that takes a fibred category to its total category (i.e. the oplax colimit of the corresponding diagram of categories under straightening). A generalised form of Hofmann–Streicher lifting that can be applied to categories other than universes is then obtained by conjugating this right 2-adjoint with duality involutions.</fr:p><fr:p>In joint work with <fr:link
type="local"
href="danielgratzer.xml"
addr="danielgratzer"
title="Daniel Gratzer">Daniel Gratzer</fr:link> and <fr:link
type="local"
href="andrewslattery.xml"
addr="andrewslattery"
title="Andrew Slattery">Andrew Slattery</fr:link>, we have constructed a <fr:em>relative</fr:em> version of the 2-functorial Hofmann–Streicher lifting: given a fibration <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo
lspace=".1em"
rspace=".2em">:</mml:mo> <mml:mi>𝓐</mml:mi><mml:mo>→</mml:mo> <mml:mi>𝓑</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math>, we have a 2-functor <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>Δ</mml:mi><mml:mi>p</mml:mi></mml:msub> <mml:mo
lspace=".1em"
rspace=".2em">:</mml:mo> <mml:mrow><mml:mi>𝐅𝐢𝐛</mml:mi>
  <mml:mrow>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[(]]></mml:mo>
   <mml:mi>𝓑</mml:mi>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[)]]></mml:mo>
  </mml:mrow>
 </mml:mrow><mml:mo>→</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>𝐅𝐢𝐛</mml:mi>
  <mml:mrow>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[(]]></mml:mo>
   <mml:mi>𝓐</mml:mi>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[)]]></mml:mo>
  </mml:mrow>
 </mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math> which is <fr:em>not</fr:em> base change but rather (we conjecture) right <fr:em>pseudo</fr:em>-adjoint to the 2-functor <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>Σ</mml:mi><mml:mi>p</mml:mi></mml:msub> <mml:mo
lspace=".1em"
rspace=".2em">:</mml:mo> <mml:mrow><mml:mi>𝐅𝐢𝐛</mml:mi>
  <mml:mrow>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[(]]></mml:mo>
   <mml:mi>𝓑</mml:mi>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[)]]></mml:mo>
  </mml:mrow>
 </mml:mrow><mml:mo>→</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>𝐅𝐢𝐛</mml:mi>
  <mml:mrow>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[(]]></mml:mo>
   <mml:mi>𝓐</mml:mi>
   <mml:mo
fence="true"><![CDATA[)]]></mml:mo>
  </mml:mrow>
 </mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math> that sends a fibration <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>q</mml:mi><mml:mo
lspace=".1em"
rspace=".2em">:</mml:mo> <mml:mi>𝓔</mml:mi><mml:mo>→</mml:mo><mml:mi>𝓐</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math> to the composite fibration <mml:math
xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo>∘</mml:mo><mml:mi>q</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo
lspace=".2em"
rspace=".2em">:</mml:mo> <mml:mi>𝓔</mml:mi><mml:mo>→</mml:mo><mml:mi>𝓑</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math>. A relative version of Hofmann–Streicher lifting could give a more regular theory to the practice of computing <fr:em>internal</fr:em> liftings of lifted universes.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
